org.gearvrf

Class GVRPicker

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.gearvrf.GVRPicker

  • public class GVRPicker
extends java.lang.Object
    Finds the scene objects you are pointing to. For a scene object to be pickable, it must have a GVREyePointeeHolder attached and enabled.

    This picker "casts" a ray into the screen graph, and returns each enabled GVREyePointeeHolder that the ray hits, sorted by distance from the camera. Use GVRComponent.getOwnerObject() to map the eye pointee holder to a scene object.

    • Method Detail

      • pickScene

        public static final GVREyePointeeHolder[] pickScene(GVRScene scene,
                                                    float ox,
                                                    float oy,
                                                    float oz,
                                                    float dx,
                                                    float dy,
                                                    float dz)
        Casts a ray into the scene graph, and returns the objects it intersects. The ray is defined by its origin [ox, oy, oz] and its direction [dx, dy, dz].

        The ray origin may be [0, 0, 0] and the direction components should be normalized from -1 to 1: Note that the y direction runs from -1 at the bottom to 1 at the top. To construct a picking ray originating at the user's head and pointing into the scene along the camera lookat vector, pass in 0, 0, 0 for the origin and 0, 0, -1 for the direction.

        Note: The hit location is stored in the native eye pointee holder during the ray casting operation: It is only valid until the next ray cast operation. That is, either the short pickScene(), or the long pickScene(), or findObjects() calls will invalidate previous hit data. There are two ways to avoid getting invalid hit data:

        • Use the high-level findObjects() method, which returns a list of GVRPicker.GVRPickedObject: each picked object pairs a GVRSceneObject with the hit data.
        • Write your code so that you never call ray casting operation until you have retrieved the previous operations hit data. (This is easy, if you only ever do picking from the GL thread. It's significantly harder if you are using multiple threads.)
        Parameters:
        scene - The GVRScene with all the objects to be tested.
        ox - The x coordinate of the ray origin.
        oy - The y coordinate of the ray origin.
        oz - The z coordinate of the ray origin.
        dx - The x vector of the ray direction.
        dy - The y vector of the ray direction.
        dz - The z vector of the ray direction.
        Returns:
        The eye pointee holders penetrated by the ray, sorted by distance from the camera rig. Use GVRComponent.getOwnerObject() to get the corresponding scene objects.

      • pickScene

        public static final GVREyePointeeHolder[] pickScene(GVRScene scene)
        Tests the GVRSceneObjects contained within scene against the camera rig's lookat vector.

        Note: The hit location is stored in the native eye pointee holder during the ray casting operation: It is only valid until the next ray cast operation. That is, either the short pickScene(), or the long pickScene(), or findObjects() calls will invalidate previous hit data. There are two ways to avoid getting invalid hit data:

        • Use the high-level findObjects() method, which returns a list of GVRPicker.GVRPickedObject: each picked object pairs a GVRSceneObject with the hit data.
        • Write your code so that you never call ray casting operation until you have retrieved the previous operations hit data. (This is easy, if you only ever do picking from the GL thread. It's significantly harder if you are using multiple threads.)
        Parameters:
        scene - The GVRScene with all the objects to be tested.
        Returns:
        the GVREyePointeeHolders which are penetrated by the picking ray. The holders are sorted by distance from the camera rig.

      • findObjects

        public static final java.util.List<GVRPicker.GVRPickedObject> findObjects(GVRScene scene,
                                                                          float ox,
                                                                          float oy,
                                                                          float oz,
                                                                          float dx,
                                                                          float dy,
                                                                          float dz)
        Casts a ray into the scene graph, and returns the objects it intersects. The ray is defined by its origin [ox, oy, oz] and its direction [dx, dy, dz].

        The ray origin may be [0, 0, 0] and the direction components should be normalized from -1 to 1: Note that the y direction runs from -1 at the bottom to 1 at the top. To construct a picking ray originating at the user's head and pointing into the scene along the camera lookat vector, pass in 0, 0, 0 for the origin and 0, 0, -1 for the direction.

        This method is higher-level and easier to use than pickScene(): Not only does it return the hit scene object (not its holder) and the hit location directly, it is thread safe in a way that the lower-level methods are not: The hit location is stored in the native eye pointee holder during the ray casting operation and it is only valid until the next ray cast operation. This method guarantees that only one thread at a time is doing a ray cast into a particular scene graph, and it extracts the hit data during within its synchronized block. You can then examine the return list without worrying about another thread corrupting your hit data.

        Parameters:
        scene - The GVRScene with all the objects to be tested.
        ox - The x coordinate of the ray origin.
        oy - The y coordinate of the ray origin.
        oz - The z coordinate of the ray origin.
        dx - The x vector of the ray direction.
        dy - The y vector of the ray direction.
        dz - The z vector of the ray direction.
        Returns:
        A list of GVRPicker.GVRPickedObject, sorted by distance from the camera rig. Each GVRPicker.GVRPickedObject contains the object within the GVREyePointeeHolder along with the hit location. (Note that the hit location is actually the point where the cast ray intersected the holder's axis-aligned bounding box, which may not be exactly where the ray would intersect the scene object itself.)
        Since:
        1.6.6
